{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Renamed files appear only in the renamed category, not as added+deleted.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"THREE-GATE for Integration→System: (1) Evidence: \"Renamed files appear in their own category and are not also counted as a deletion plus an addition.\" (2) Concrete miss at lower level: an integration test with mocked git output can miss real `git` rename detection behavior/thresholds and status encoding, so code passes mocks but misclassifies real repo renames. (3) Boundary type: real-infra (real git subprocess + repository/index state). Rejected higher levels: behavior text is purely git diff categorization, with no AI/ML decision (disqualifies Agentic) and no multi-agent sequence (disqualifies Workflow).","test_description":"Create a real temp git repo, commit baseline, perform `git mv` and content edits that still qualify as rename, run the CLI as a subprocess, and assert report shows the file only in `renamed` with no corresponding add/delete entries.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.7,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Binary-file diffs do not crash the tool and binary files are counted.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"THREE-GATE for Integration→System: (1) Evidence: \"Diffs that include binary files do not cause the tool to crash; binary files are counted.\" (2) Concrete miss at lower level: mocked diff payloads may not reproduce real binary diff output/exit-code/stderr behavior from `git`, so decode/parsing crashes only appear with real subprocess output. (3) Boundary type: real-infra. Rejected higher levels: no model output quality or non-deterministic AI path is described, and no multi-agent pipeline is present.","test_description":"In a real temp repo, commit a binary file change (e.g., image bytes), run the CLI subprocess against that history, assert exit code is success an